Preprocessing¶

In [125]:
###### Preprocessing ##############################################################

# Titles to lower case
data['title'] = data['title'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x.lower() for x in x.split()))

# To see some example of data, uncomment below
#print(data['title'].head())

# Remove punctuation
data['title'] = data['title'].str.replace('[^\w\s]','')

# Remove numerical values (regex replacement)
data['title'] = data['title'].str.replace('\d+', '')

# Remove some words that may be uninformative about the topic
wordlist = ("uk", "great britain", "england", "wales", "britain", "germany", "economic", "market", "british", "economy", "big ideas", "evidence")
for x in wordlist:
    data['title'] = data['title'].str.replace(x,'')

# Remove stop words (pronouns, etc.). This uses a database embedded in NLTK
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
stop = stopwords.words('english')
data['title'] = data['title'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x for x in x.split() if x not in stop))

TOPIC MODELLING¶

Estimate LDA model using single words¶

In [131]:
# Pandas to list
titles = [x for x in data['title']]

titles_tok = [doc.split() for doc in titles]

# Importing Gensim
import gensim
from gensim import corpora
import pickle

# Creating the term dictionary of our courpus, where every unique term is assigned an index.
dictionary = corpora.Dictionary(titles_tok)

# Converting list of titles (corpus) into Document Term Matrix using dictionary prepared above.
corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in titles_tok]    
pickle.dump(corpus, open('corpus.pkl', 'wb'))
dictionary.save('dictionary.gensim')

# Running and Trainign LDA model on the document term matrix.
ldamodel = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus, num_topics = 10, id2word=dictionary, passes=15)
ldamodel.save('model10.gensim')

# Print the topics (first four elements only)
for topic in ldamodel.print_topics(num_topics=10, num_words=3):
    print(topic)

Plot evolution of topics over time¶

In [133]:
# Estimate 7 topics to simplify graph
lda = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus, num_topics = 7, id2word=dictionary, passes=15)

# The function below returns most likely topic
def top_topic(title):
    bow = dictionary.doc2bow(title.split())
    topic_dist = lda.get_document_topics(bow) 
    topic_dist.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])
    topic_h = topic_dist[0][0]
    return topic_h
       
# Predict Top Topic
data['top_topic'] = data['title'].apply(lambda x: top_topic(str(x)))
  
# Distributions of topics over time
yeartopic =  pd.crosstab(data["pubyear"],data["top_topic"],margins=False)

# Plot Distribution of topics (first label)
labels = [x for x in lda.print_topics(num_topics=7, num_words=4)]
labels = [x[1] for x in labels]
plt.show(yeartopic.plot.line().legend(labels,bbox_to_anchor=(1.04,1), loc="upper left").set_title('Evolution of Detected Topics over Time'))

Evolution of bi-grams detected topics over time¶

In [135]:
# Estimate 7 topics to simplify graph
lda = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpusBi, num_topics = 7, id2word=dictionaryBi, passes=15)

# The function below returns most likely topic
def top_topic_bigram(title):
    row_bigram = list(nltk.bigrams(title.split()))
    row_bigram_p = [str(x[0]) + " " + str(x[1]) for x in row_bigram]
    bow = dictionaryBi.doc2bow( row_bigram_p)
    topic_dist = lda.get_document_topics(bow) 
    topic_dist.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])
    topic_h = topic_dist[0][0]
    return topic_h

    
# Predict Top Topic
data['top_topic_bigram'] = data['title'].apply(lambda x: top_topic_bigram(str(x)))
  
# Distributions of topics over time
yeartopic =  pd.crosstab(data["pubyear"],data["top_topic_bigram"],margins=False)

# Plot Distribution of topics (first label)
labels = [x for x in lda.print_topics(num_topics=7, num_words=3)]
labels = [x[1] for x in labels]
plt.show(yeartopic.plot.line().legend(labels,bbox_to_anchor=(1.04,1), loc="upper left").set_title('Evolution of Detected Topics Bi-Grams over Time'))

The following code estimates a different model (Hierarchical Dirichlet Process - HDP) that do not require a fixed number of topics but it has a maximum number of topics to fit.¶

In [136]:
from gensim import models
import pyLDAvis.gensim as gensimvis

hdp = models.hdpmodel.HdpModel(corpus, dictionary, T=20)                                     
hdp.save('hdp.model')

# Note that below I also change the distance function to mmds (affects how the clusters are defined)
vis_data = gensimvis.prepare(hdp, corpus, dictionary, mds='mmds', sort_topics=True)
pyLDAvis.display(vis_data)
